https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenbak-1: The Kenbak-1 (1971) used small scale integration transistor-transistor logic (TTL) ICs and had 256 bytes of memory.  It was priced at USD 750 and sold only 40 units.[1]
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Datapoint_: Datapoint 2200 (shipped 1971) was the first machine designed to use a microprocessor, but when Intel could not deliver the 8008 in time, they released the machine using discrete logic.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Educ-8: The Educ-8 (1975) was an Electronics Australia magazine project describing a computer built from TTL ICs.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MicroSyste: MicroSystems International's CPS-1, using a locally produced microprocessor based on the design of the Intel 4004. First built in 1972, a small number shipped in early 1973.[6]
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micral: Micral N (1973) was awarded the title of "the first personal computer using a microprocessor by a panel at the Computer History Museum in 1986.[7]
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sord_Compu: Sord Computer Corporation's SMP80/08, based on the Intel 8008, was announced in early 1973, but never commercially released. It was followed by the SMP80/x, which debuted in May 1974 and used the Intel 8080.[8]
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MCM/70: MCM/70 was a 1974 Intel 8008-based design, primarily designed to run APL. According to the IEEE Annals of Computer History, the MCM/70 is the earliest commercial, non-kit personal computer.[9]
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM_5100: IBM 5100 was possibly the first portable microcomputer. Most people think the famous IBM PC (the 5150) was IBM's first micro but there were a number of microcomputer models released by IBM from 1975.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MPT8080: MPT8080 Microtutor, an Intel 8080–based microprocessor trainer introduced 1977.  As recently as 2008, it remained in academic use.[10]  As of 2011, the MPT8080 was still available for sale.
